    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i also noticed a lot of my other sentences use \"was\" or \"were\" a lot. is there a specific way to tell if a sentence is using passive voice or if it's just a normal way of writing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're on the lookout for passive voice, a common pitfall in writing. Passive voice can be identified by the verb \"was\" or \"were\" at the end of a sentence, but it's not the only indicator. Look for sentences that start with \"was\" or \"were\" followed by a verb, or sentences where the subject is performing an action on something else (e.g., \"The results were analyzed\"). In your case, sentences like \"The researchers were using a t-test\" or \"The results were analyzed\" are examples of passive voice. To make them more active, try rephrasing them to focus on the subject performing the action, like \"The researchers used a t-test\" or \"The results were analyzed by the researchers.\"",
      "source": "target",
